# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dbt-transform
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] It started at RJMetrics in 2016 as a solution to add basic transformation capabilities to Stitch (acquired by Talend in 2018).
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] The earliest versions of dbt allowed analysts to contribute to the data transformation process following the best practices of software engineering.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] From the beginning, dbt was open source.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] In 2018, the dbt Labs team (then called Fishtown Analytics) released a commercial product on top of dbt Core.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] In April 2020, dbt Labs announced its Series A led by Andreessen Horowitz.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] In November, dbt Labs announced its Series B led by Andreessen Horowitz and Sequoia.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] And in June 2021, dbt Labs raised its Series C led by Altimeter, Sequoia, and Andreessen Horowitz.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] In February 2022, the company raised $222 million for its Series D, at a $4.2 billion valuation.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] Dbt enables analytics engineers to transform data in their warehouses by writing select statements, and turns these select statements into tables and views.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] Dbt does the transformation (T) in extract, load, transform (ELT) processes – it does not extract or load data, but is designed to be performant at transforming data already inside of a warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] Dbt has the goal of allowing analysts to work more like software engineers, in line with the dbt viewpoint.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] Dbt uses YAML files to declare properties.
[src:dbt-transform/data-build-tool] `seed` is a type of reference table used in dbt for static or infrequently changed data, like for example country codes or lookup tables), which are CSV based and typically stored in a seeds folder.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] In computing, **data transformation** is the process of converting data from one format or structure into another format or structure.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] It is a fundamental aspect of most data integration and data management tasks such as data wrangling, data warehousing, data integration and application integration.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Data transformation can be simple or complex based on the required changes to the data between the source (initial) data and the target (final) data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Data transformation is typically performed via a mixture of manual and automated steps.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Tools and technologies used for data transformation can vary widely based on the format, structure, complexity, and volume of the data being transformed.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] A master data recast is another form of data transformation where the entire database of data values is transformed or recast without extracting the data from the database.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] All data in a well-designed database is directly or indirectly related to a limited set of master database tables by a network of foreign key constraints.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Each foreign key constraint is dependent upon a unique database index from the parent database table.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Therefore, when the proper master database table is recast with a different unique index, the directly and indirectly related data are also recast or restated.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] The directly and indirectly related data may also still be viewed in the original form since the original unique index still exists with the master data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Also, the database recast must be done in such a way as to not impact the applications architecture software.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] When the data mapping is indirect via a mediating data model, the process is also called **data mediation**.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Data transformation can be divided into the following steps, each applicable as needed based on the complexity of the transformation required.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] These steps are often the focus of developers or technical data analysts who may use multiple specialized tools to perform their tasks.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Traditionally, data transformation has been a bulk or batch process, whereby developers write code or implement transformation rules in a data integration tool, and then execute that code or those rules on large volumes of data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] This process can follow the linear set of steps as described in the data transformation process above.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Batch data transformation is the cornerstone of virtually all data integration technologies such as data warehousing, data migration and application integration.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] When data must be transformed and delivered with low latency, the term "microbatch" is often used.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] This refers to small batches of data (e.g. a small number of rows or a small set of data objects) that can be processed very quickly and delivered to the target system when needed.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Traditional data transformation processes have served companies well for decades.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] The various tools and technologies (data profiling, data visualization, data cleansing, data integration etc.) have matured and most (if not all) enterprises transform enormous volumes of data that feed internal and external applications, data warehouses and other data stores.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] This traditional process also has limitations that hamper its overall efficiency and effectiveness.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] The people who need to use the data (e.g. business users) do not play a direct role in the data transformation process.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Typically, users hand over the data transformation task to developers who have the necessary coding or technical skills to define the transformations and execute them on the data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] This process leaves the bulk of the work of defining the required transformations to the developer, which often in turn do not have the same domain knowledge as the business user.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] The developer interprets the business user requirements and implements the related code/logic.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] This has the potential of introducing errors into the process (through misinterpreted requirements), and also increases the time to arrive at a solution.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] This problem has given rise to the need for agility and self-service in data integration (i.e. empowering the user of the data and enabling them to transform the data themselves interactively).
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] There are companies that provide self-service data transformation tools.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] They are aiming to efficiently analyze, map and transform large volumes of data without the technical knowledge and process complexity that currently exists.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] While these companies use traditional batch transformation, their tools enable more interactivity for users through visual platforms and easily repeated scripts.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Still, there might be some compatibility issues (e.g. new data sources like IoT may not work correctly with older tools) and compliance limitations due to the difference in data governance, preparation and audit practices.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Although interactive data transformation follows the same data integration process steps as batch data integration, the key difference is that the steps are not necessarily followed in a linear fashion and typically don't require significant technical skills for completion.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] There are a number of companies that provide interactive data transformation tools, including Trifacta, Alteryx and Paxata.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] They are aiming to efficiently analyze, map and transform large volumes of data while at the same time abstracting away some of the technical complexity and processes which take place under the hood.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Interactive data transformation solutions provide an integrated visual interface that combines the previously disparate steps of data analysis, data mapping and code generation/execution and data inspection.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] That is, if changes are made at one step (like for example renaming), the software automatically updates the preceding or following steps accordingly.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Interfaces for interactive data transformation incorporate visualizations to show the user patterns and anomalies in the data so they can identify erroneous or outlying values.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Once they've finished transforming the data, the system can generate executable code/logic, which can be executed or applied to subsequent similar data sets.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] There are numerous languages available for performing data transformation.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Many transformation languages require a grammar to be provided.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] In many cases, the grammar is structured using something closely resembling Backus–Naur form (BNF).
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] There are numerous languages available for such purposes varying in their accessibility (cost) and general usefulness.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Additionally, companies such as Trifacta and Paxata have developed domain-specific transformational languages (DSL) for servicing and transforming datasets.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] The development of domain-specific languages has been linked to increased productivity and accessibility for non-technical users.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Trifacta's “Wrangle” is an example of such a domain-specific language.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Another advantage of the recent domain-specific transformational languages trend is that a domain-specific transformational language can abstract the underlying execution of the logic defined in the domain-specific transformational language.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] They can also utilize that same logic in various processing engines, such as Spark, MapReduce, and Dataflow.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] In other words, with a domain-specific transformational language, the transformation language is not tied to the underlying engine.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] Although transformational languages are typically best suited for transformation, something as simple as regular expressions can be used to achieve useful transformation.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] A text editor like vim, emacs or TextPad supports the use of regular expressions with arguments.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] This would allow all instances of a particular pattern to be replaced with another pattern using parts of the original pattern.
[src:dbt-transform/data-transformation] In other words, all instances of a function invocation of foo with three arguments, followed by a function invocation with two arguments would be replaced with a single function invocation using some or all of the original set of arguments.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:dbt-transform/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
