[src:dbt-transform/extract-load-transform] Some of the benefits of an ELT process include speed and the ability to handle both structured and unstructured data.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In computing, a **materialized view** is a database object that contains the results of a query.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] For example, it may be a local copy of data located remotely, or may be a subset of the rows and/or columns of a table or join result, or may be a summary using an aggregate function.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] The process of setting up a materialized view is sometimes called **materialization**.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] This is a form of caching the results of a query, similar to memoization of the value of a function in functional languages, and it is sometimes described as a form of precomputation.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] As with other forms of precomputation, database users typically use materialized views for performance reasons, i.e. as a form of optimization.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Materialized views that store data based on remote tables were also known as snapshots (deprecated Oracle terminology).
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In any database management system following the relational model, a view is a virtual table representing the result of a database query.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Whenever a query or an update addresses an ordinary view's virtual table, the DBMS converts these into queries or updates against the underlying base tables.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] A materialized view takes a different approach: the query result is cached as a concrete ("materialized") table (rather than a view as such) that may be updated from the original base tables from time to time.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] This enables much more efficient access, at the cost of extra storage and of some data being potentially out-of-date.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Materialized views find use especially in data warehousing scenarios, where frequent queries of the actual base tables can be expensive.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In a materialized view, indexes can be built on any column.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In contrast, in a normal view, it's typically only possible to exploit indexes on columns that come directly from (or have a mapping to) indexed columns in the base tables; often this functionality is not offered at all.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Materialized views were implemented first by the Oracle Database: the Query rewrite feature was added from version 8i.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In PostgreSQL, version 9.3 and newer natively support materialized views.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In version 9.3, a materialized view is not auto-refreshed, and is populated only at time of creation (unless `WITH NO DATA` is used).
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] It may be refreshed later manually using `REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW`.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In version 9.4, the refresh may be concurrent with selects on the materialized view if `CONCURRENTLY` is used.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Microsoft SQL Server differs from other RDBMS by the way of implementing materialized view via a concept known as "Indexed Views".
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] The main difference is that such views do not require a refresh because they are in fact always synchronized to the original data of the tables that compound the view.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] To achieve this, it is necessary that the lines of origin and destination are "deterministic" in their mapping, which limits the types of possible queries to do this.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] This mechanism has been realised since the 2000 version of SQL Server.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Apache Kafka (since v0.10.2), Apache Spark (since v2.0), Apache Flink, Kinetica DB, Materialize, RisingWave, and Epsio all support materialized views on streams of data.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Materialized views are also supported in Sybase SQL Anywhere.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] In IBM Db2, they are called "materialized query tables".
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] ClickHouse supports materialized views that automatically refresh on merges.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] MySQL doesn't support materialized views natively, but workarounds can be implemented by using triggers or stored procedures or by using the open-source application Flexviews.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Materialized views can be implemented in Amazon DynamoDB using data modification events captured by DynamoDB Streams.
[src:dbt-transform/materialized-view] Google announced in 8 April 2020 the availability of materialized views for BigQuery as a beta release.
